5|$|Jordan led the NBA {{in scoring}} in 10 seasons (NBA record) and tied Wilt Chamberlain's record of seven {{consecutive}} scoring titles. He {{was also a}} fixture on the NBA All-Defensive First Team, making the roster nine times (NBA record shared with Gary Payton, Kevin Garnett and <b>Kobe</b> <b>Bryant).</b> Jordan also holds the top career regular season and playoff scoring averages of 30.1 and 33.4 points per game, respectively. By 1998, the season of his Finals-winning shot against the Jazz, he was well known throughout the league as a clutch performer. In the regular season, Jordan was the Bulls' primary threat {{in the final seconds}} of a close game and in the playoffs, Jordan would always demand the ball at crunch time. Jordan's total of 5,987 points in the playoffs is the second-highest in NBA history. He retired with 32,292 points in regular season play, placing him fourth on the NBA's all-time scoring list behind Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Karl Malone, and <b>Kobe</b> <b>Bryant.</b>|$|E
